":"Moles","meanings":["English: variant of   Moll  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Catalan: habitational name from any of various minor places called Moles, from the plural of <i>mola</i> (see   Mola  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Meulles (Calvados). See also   Moyles  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William DE MEULES 1st was born in 1059, in Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. William MEULES. He died in Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France."},"et":{"1059–":"1059–Surnud","1061–Female":"1061–Surnud","1082–Female":"1082–Surnud","1059–Male":"1059–Surnud","about 1082":"umbes 1082","1059":"1059","1061":"1061","1082":"1082","Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1059–":"1059–Kuollut","1061–Female":"1061–Kuollut","1082–Female":"1082–Kuollut","1059–Male":"1059–Kuollut","about 1082":"noin 1082","1059":"1059","1061":"1061","1082":"1082","Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1059–":"1059–Décédé","1061–Female":"1061–Décédée","1082–Female":"1082–Décédée","1059–Male":"1059–Décédé","about 1082":"environ 1082","1059":"1059","1061":"1061","1082":"1082","Brionne, Eure, Normand